segments.text: But anyhow, Jack McCreary, my roommate, Wayne was responsible for his going to Harvard Business School.
He touched a lot of students.
Unbelievable guy.
Did any of you or any of your acquaintances ever get the lecture from Wayne Stark that some students call the green couch treatment?
I don't recall that.
What I do remember about Wayne Stark, particularly when I became president of the association,
And Wayne was still pretty active at that time.
I'm not sure he was still director, but he was.
One thing, he had a file system that would absolutely blow your mind.
And he had a file on every student that had come into contact.
Not the J. Edgar Hoover kind of file, but the kind of file that
and just helped him get kids placed into graduate schools and things like that.
He showed me those files one time.
In fact, I was asking about some person.
He said, well, let me show you this.
And I was asking about some person.
I put out the file, and I had the guy's professional history.
That's just my main recollection of him.
All right.
Guyon Hall.
Do you remember any activities in Guyon Hall?
Oh, sure.
What happened at Guyon Hall?
Guy Hall was where we had, I believe, where we had a lot of the entertainers come in from Guy Hall.
Elvis Presley came there as my freshman year.
Buddy Holly, as I told you outside this tape, was my classmate in A&M, and I first saw Elvis Presley in Lubbock when he came in 1955 in the opening act where Elvis was Buddy Holly.
The only time they ever appeared on the same stage.
That was at A&M?
No, no, at Lubbock High School.
So I'd seen Elvis one time before A&M.
I saw Elvis two times, one at Lubbock and one at A&M.

Interesting side note there, when Buddy Holly opened up the Elvis Presley show, he went through these gyrations and he was looked by a local guy and was moved off the stage because everybody thought this high school nerd was trying to act like Elvis Presley.
Little did we know that the guy was a musical genius.
And it's absolutely revered in England, though, much more so in the United States.
But Elvis Presley is one I remember.
We had the four freshmen.
I remember that because everybody called him Fish, the four fish.
Matt Davis, also from another period one time, in somebody's place.
He was just starting to make it big.
I may be wrong about that.
I might have seen Matt Davis after I graduated, but he came to the A&M.
So the Guyon Hall and G. Raleigh White had just been constructed, so that was the place where we had the entertainers and so forth.
Religious emphasis week, was that still going on when you were there?
Yes, it was.
Can you remember it?
Can you describe it?
The only thing that comes to my mind on that is that we, in our particular outfit, you had to go to church.
You didn't have a choice, even if you didn't want to.
Religious emphasis week.
I remember we had it, and it was a routine thing all four years, but I don't...
Most of us went to church anyhow.
It wouldn't have been a deal.
Yeah.
Describe that.
Where did the typical students go to?
To whatever religion they were raised in.
And where were those churches located?
All around the campus.
Everything Jewish, Catholic, Protestant.
Obviously, most of us were Protestants.
I went to the Indian Methodist Church there.
I got a lot off the campus and just north of the campus there.
Let's discuss student diversity.
generalize about the student body in your day, it was basically what?
Basically, part Anglo-Saxon Protestants.
The biggest minority in him when I was there, and it was quite a sizable minority, were Hispanics.
And how were they treated?
It was kind of interesting.
And it was very ethnic, and it was done in a very positive sort of way.
If you were a Catholic, you were just lambasted.
in a funny sort of way.
If you had a girlfriend who was just marginally good looking and we were lambasted, it was above the kind of deal.
Hispanics were treated like Hispanics but with a tremendous amount of respect.
Because most of them came from very poor families down the border.
First ones in their whole families to ever get an education.
So they were treated with a tremendous amount of respect.
Were there any Jewish students?
Yes, a few.
And how were they treated?
It's kind of funny.
Most of us didn't even know any difference between Jews and Protestants.
We didn't know.
You know, we'd been raised outside, far away from most Jewish people.
So, to me, they're just like a Methodist or a Baptist or a Presbyterian.
Were there any Asian?
Virtually none.
Virtually none.
And, of course, we were undergraduates.
At that time, the graduate school down here was very small.
And, as you know, you get most of, a lot of your foreign students in the
in graduate school.

We did have, and we couldn't differentiate, we didn't have a lot of people of Latin backgrounds, and it was pretty hotbed then for people in South America, as well as Mexico, to send their, particularly in agriculture, more than engineering, to send their sons to A&M.
So we had quite a few people of Latin backgrounds.
And how were they treated?
Oh, most of them were not the core.
because they had no military obligation to the United States.
So we didn't really associate with a lot of them, but they were civilians.
No differently than anybody else.
And I assume that almost everybody, faculty, staff, or student, had a nickname in those days.
Just about.
And were those nicknames intended to be negative or positive?
It was more of the ethos of that day.
You're always criticized in a good sort of way.
The old saying is, I'd rather be criticized by friends than praised by enemies, and that kind of held true.
The more they criticize you, the more they like you.
In fact, I think they even put nicknames in the yearbook.
I know they did for many years.
Yeah, I think they did back in my time.
Athletics.
You mentioned the football coach.
Tell me about football during your time.
Well, football had gone from...
And of course, I'd followed A&M football since the 40s.
It languished in the early 50s.
And then Bear Bryant came in in 1954.
I entered A&M in 55.
So I was there at the exponential growth of football interest and actually at the apogee at that time.
Bear Bryant was coached at A&M three years out of my four.
So it was the hottest thing on campus.
Who were the famous football heroes in your
Well, of course, we had to memorize the whole team as a freshman.
I had to know everybody on the team.
So an upperclassman, I'd sit next to an upperclassman, somebody would make a play, I'd have to tell them who it was.
They wouldn't buy a program.
They used freshmen for their program, let's say 50 cents.
So I knew every person on the team, not personally, but just their numbers.
Obviously, we had John Crow and Lloyd Taylor and Jimmy Wright.
Charlie Krueger, those were some of the more famous.
Who were those two guys that played in the two starting ends?
John Tracy played one and Gene Stallage played one.
Gene Stallage was an end.
And then another end that was from Breckenridge was a fellow named Keith.
Oh, Bobby Drake Keith.
Sure.
Bobby Drake Keith.
Dear friend.
Is that right?
He's now president of what used to be Arkansas Power and Light.
No kidding.
It's Inter-G Arkansas now.
Actually, Bobby Drake Keith graduated in about 57, as I recall, or 56.
He was a little, he was not.
He and Beebs were one year behind Crow.
That's right.
The Junction Survivors formed really the core team.
They were the preceding class before the big recruiting teams.
which that Bear Blount did in 55.
So the class of those that came as freshmen in 56, or 55, I guess, were the ones who really propelled them to national status.
Describe a typical home football Saturday of routine for a student.
Well, if you're a freshman, you sit in the end zone with shaved heads and no girlfriend.
That was kind of the tradition.
Sophomore, you moved toward the goal line with maybe a girlfriend.
Junior year, you moved about the 20-yard line with a girlfriend.
Senior year, you maybe had two girlfriends, but sitting on close to 50, so it kind of been one year.
We didn't watch any of the other games.
Kyle Field held about 38,000 to 40,000 at that time.
They just made the first edition of the new press box.
It was kind of weird looking.
Not a second debt, just an extension on the west side.
Was there anything that happened on Friday nights?
Oh, yeah, sure.
We had the midnight yell practice.
Describe that.
Well, midnight yell practice would go to the Grove.
And it was just a great time.
Band marching in.
He would have you, if you had a day chat, you'd go to midnight yell practice.
It was a lot of fun.
And then you'd normally have a dance Saturday night after the game.
Did anything happen after midnight yell practice was over?
Normally not.
No, I'm not.
We would go to individual parties or something, get back in about 3 o'clock in the morning, but nothing orchestrated after midnight kill practice.
Then Saturday morning, what?
Saturday morning, you could sack in, as I recall.
I don't think you had a formation Saturday morning with a football game because you marched in the game.
So you'd congregate around 10 or 11 o'clock and march in, as I recall.
And since they were winning almost all those games, what happened at the end of the game?
We'd throw you out there.
At that time,
You throw them in the fountain.
I'm trying to think.
We didn't have much of a fountain at that time.
As I recall, we had kind of a little bowl deal over where the rudder center is now, which wasn't there at that time.
And you just put them in that and you'd throw a bucket of water on them.
It wasn't a big fountain, but it was the same kind of condition, if you won, which we normally did.
And since the Aggies were winning, what happened after touchdowns?
Well, you do the same as you do now.
You kiss your date.
Let's see, G. Raleigh, tell me about a basketball.
Barry Brunn, I believe, was an athletic director when he first got there.
I think that was part of the package.
He brought in a guy named Bobby Rogers, who was, I believe it was Bobby Rogers.
No, I'm sorry, it was one before he'd actually written a book.
It was one before Bobby Rogers.
From up at LaSalle.
I think that's right.
I'm trying to think of his name.
I can't remember his name.
But Bobby Rogers was coached most of the time I was there.
I had one of the people at my wedding was a basketball player, a guy named Neil Swisher, who was also a civil engineer.
He and I were classmates and went to a lot of classes together.
Good friend, great basketball player.
We had, I think, kind of a middle-of-the-run basketball team at that time.
We weren't real bad, weren't real good.
Did you all go to the games?
Sure, went to every game.
And what kind of special curriculum was there for athletes then?
I had quite a few athletes in my class, Bear Bryant type athletes.
Most of them are not scholars.
I've heard that he recruited 100 kids in 1955, which we graduated on time.
That's probably right.
I think a lot more graduated.
But most of the athletes took, he had a few exceptions.
Most of the athletes were not, you know, were football players, took PE.
Certainly a few exceptions.
We had John Crow was a very bright guy, Charlie Milstead, an engineer.
In fact, Charlie and I are kind of the same profession.
And Stallings and... Gene Stallings was a good serious student.
And Keith was a... Bobby Drake Keith was.
I mean, there were certainly... Geologically...
I'm talking about the class after that of the hundred, not the Stallings crowd.
Other campus organizations for students, singing cadets, what were they like then?
Great, great like they are now.
Any of your friends in the singing?
Very few.
For some reason, other than Buddy Holly, I've never hung around people who had any musical talent.
The band, describe it in your day.
It was big for that time, I think about 150, something like that, members.
Room band, white band.
Did you all have a respect for the band?
Certainly, a bit.
In fact, a lot of my classmates were in a band.
The student government, was it?
I think it was kind of secondary, really.
The campus centered around the Corps of Cadets.
And you always had a president of a senior class, a president of a junior class.
But the status in the Corps was far more of a factor than being an officer in the class.
Student politics was just really, I didn't know the difference between Republican or Democratic, conservative or liberal, I mean.
I just didn't know that.
In terms of prestige, of all the extracurricular offices on the campus, the Corps ranked highest?
Oh, by far.
And then what?
Probably where you were a distinguished student or not.
That was a big deal.
Or a distinguished military student.
We were called DMS or a distinguished student.
Yell leader, band commander?
Yell leaders were always a different breed.
Kind of a wild bunch of people.
Most of the Yale leaders, with a few exceptions, were wild, uninhibited, non-scholars, great guys.
Certainly true of my class, kind of smoky high.
But Yale leaders were certainly respected.
But again, I think the corps status emasculated all other, all other, how you go in a corps, not necessarily just the rank, but the designation's very important to you.
Singing cadets?
Were they around then?
Sure.
Thank you for asking that.
Yeah, they were respected.
Let's see.
Don't reveal any secrets now, but were there said to be any secret fraternities around in your day?
Not in my time.
There was before I got there.
It was a big scandal.
I think it was called the TTs.
But, and I never could understand that.
When I was in high school, they had this great cataclysmic revelation of the secret fraternity, which I never really understood.
When I got there, it was a non-issue, and the whole four years I was there, it never came up.
Did the letters TT, did those letters stand for anything?
Well, they called them true tools, but I don't know what it really stood for.
A tool was a very derogatory word.
Did you ever hear of the stickers?
No.
The swastikas?
No, never heard of them.
I've heard mention of that way back into the 20s.
Let's see, you mentioned RVs.
Tell me about how did one get into the RVs and what did it mean and what were the joys?
Fabulous organization, fabulous organization.
Yesterday, you had to have a 2.0 to get in.
to even be considered being, it was out of a 3.0 system, so it would be a 2.0 out of 3.
So it would be a 3.0 under today.
Yes, I guess a 3.0, but at that time it was 2.0.
You had to have no blemishes on your record.
You had to have some military bearing.
I'm not sure there was any discrimination on what rank you were in the Corps, but that was certainly a factor.
It was pretty rigorous.
We were juniors, you had to be a junior to get in.
And very few, I would say that 80% of the RVs at that time were juniors.
Just a few stayed in as commanders.
Rainbow one certainly being one, two later.
And how many were admitted per year?
I'm going to guess there were three platoons and probably about 20 or 30 platoons.
I was going to say about 70, 80, somewhere in that range with RVs.
You had RV drill pretty regularly.
It took a lot of time.
I think you were really brought in more for your scholarship than for your military bearing, so they had to take these people and put them into a military position.
Great perks, perquisites.
Such as?
Well, the biggest one, of course, was going to Mardi Gras.
So we had, of course, going to New Orleans for Mardi Gras.
Just an unbelievable deal for us.
Describe that trip.
Well, we stayed at a naval base.
I can't remember the name of it.
I'm trying to think.
It's like Kim Johnson or something like that on Lake Pontchartrain.
It was kind of interesting because there were very rigid requirements when you actually were going through drill.
The official governor's escort, even back in those days, their cross-volunteers were.
The thing I'll never forget is that we had a drill when we were marching into Mardi Gras, which was unbelievable.
experience back in 1958.
We slapped a rifle on the pavement and turned 90 degrees and faced the crowd and went through a kind of certain routine.
And you couldn't move your eyeballs.
You couldn't do anything.
It was strictly a rigid deal.
And you would get gigged pretty hard if you did anything wrong.
And we went through a routine where, of course, the crowd was right next to us.
A rather drunken or reveling crowd.
And I hit the pavement with my rifle and turned 90 degrees and faced the crowd.
And there was a big female, a big tall gal dressed as a bunny.
And she stuck a carrot in my mouth.
So here I was with my R.E.
uniform on and a carrot sticking out of my mouth.
It absolutely broke me up.
I left the rest of the deal there and I did pretty hard.
I bit the carrot out, but I still do.
I was so tickled I lost most of my discipline.
No, that's a good story.
But it's a true story.
Anyhow, we had a great time.
Did anybody do anything unusual after hours?
Well, yeah.
We all went down to Bourbon Street and saw things we'd never seen before, and it was kind of a big scene, but nobody got in bad trouble.
Let's see.
Define hazing.
as it was practiced in those days at A&M?
We were hazed.
I would say, in retrospect, 90% of it was good and probably legal.
What did it involve?
Mainly just recollection, standing at a brace and sitting on a pink chair, which means you'd sit down at your knees at 90 degrees on a clothes hanger for long periods of time.
Good physical training.
Just going through a lot of verbal hazing as a freshman.
I got never hazed.
I never hazed as a sophomore.
And I kind of kid Ray Bowen that he made me do push-ups, which he did a lot as an RV.
Ray made us do a lot of push-ups.
I told him I still had a bad back, and I was thinking about initiating a lawsuit, but he said the statute of limitations had already cleared him.
A lot of push-ups and things like that.
I was beat one time with a board, grabbed a pooch, which I think he'll leave at that time.
And it wasn't...
It wasn't widespread.
It was very settlement-type.
Do you remember what the excuse was for that paddling?
Had you supposedly done anything wrong?
Oh, sure.
Oh, yeah.
You never really did anything seriously wrong.
They just would find something that you did wrong.
Do you remember anything that, by those standards or ours today, that was truly excessive?
No.
I really don't.
And how often was that board used?
Very seldom.
It was used and it was illegal at that time.
It was against core regulations at that time.
Who were the key core advisor, commander professionals?
General Joe Davis was the top guy, Colonel Davis.
Describe him.
Well, he was kind of, as I recall, kind of a nondescript sort of guy.
Retired military and I don't think he made a mark on up or down, but nobody
really paid much attention to him.
The attack officers, which are mostly second lieutenants or first lieutenants, were the ones that we had most of the interface with.
Colonel Joe would have all the right buzzwords, but I don't think he was really a force there, up or down.
Alright, on the campus administration, who were the key people?
The president and so forth?
Well, we had an interim president my freshman year.
I think
who was a dean of agriculture or something like that.
He was just kind of a stock gap guy.
Then, of course, Earl Rudder came in in 1957.
That was really, as you and I have discussed, off the record was kind of a cataclysmic event for A&M.
Describe his coming and the reaction, if you remember any reaction.
I remember very well.
Very controversial, right up and down the line.
And of course, the academics, the faculty didn't like him because he didn't have a PhD.
He was strictly a political tool.

Students didn't like him because he was a frog, which means, of course, coming in at midterm, which means you miss all the real hazing, which is the absolute zenith of naivety when you look at his World War II record.
So he came in with just about universal negative perception on campus, all the way from the faculty to the corps cadets, which just shows you again how naive you are when you're young sometimes.
Did he interact at all with the Corps, with the student body?
Did you all see much of him?
Frankly, I didn't too much.
I think he was so overwhelmed when he got there.

He came in as a land commissioner, as you know, Baskin-Giles problem here, and he came in with a, we all knew about that, we were cognizant of that, that he straightened out a lot of graft corruption here at the state level.
So he had that degree of respect.
But they just couldn't make the extrapolation between being a land commissioner and being a president of the
a major university.
Frankly, I don't think I ever talked with him the whole time I was at EM, nor very few of my colleagues did.
I think he was so overwhelmed trying to get a fix on the job that he didn't interface with the students a lot at that time.
As a former student, I had a lot of interface with him, obviously.
But as a student, interfacing with the president was not one of our priorities and probably not one of his at that time.
Were the project houses still being occupied by students then?
Certainly.
On both sides of the campus.
Yeah, describe those.
Well, they were just World War II barracks.
And who lived there?
Graduate students and married students.
Okay.
Let's see.
Bryan Field had closed.
Freshmen were no longer going out there.
It was an Air Force base.
Yeah, yeah.
Bryan Air Force base.
I think they used T-33 trainers.
Let's see.
Summer's job, your summer job was not a specific A&M-related job.
How did you go back and forth from Lubbock to College Station?
I didn't have a part of my junior year.
So how did you get back?
One time I took a train.
That was because we had a terrible snowstorm.
It was Christmas.
Describe that.
It was Christmas in Lubbock.
I believe it was my freshman year.
I know it was my freshman year.
Christmas.
And I drove in with some of our friends, some upperclassmen.
A guy named Jerry Davis was a pole vaulter to him from Lubbock.
And he
Of course, lived the privileged life because he was an athlete.
He had a car.
So I would drive home with him.
When we got to Lubbock over Christmas, we had a terrible snowstorm.
This was the winter of 55, 56.
The only way to get out of Lubbock was by train, so I took the train back.
All-night train.
Left Lubbock going from, actually, from L.A. to Houston.
Santa Fe, and I took the train back, and it dropped us off at Caldwell.
But other than that, I would drive.
How'd you get from Caldwell to the camp?
Hitchhike.
Tell me about Aggie hitchhiking.
Well, it was widespread in those days.
If you had a uniform on it, it sure sent you to go ride with somebody responsible.
You wouldn't think of it these days, but we hitchhiked a lot.
My freshman and sophomore year, my grandparents lived in Austin here, so I spent a lot of time in Austin.
I eventually had a girlfriend down here, so I hitchhiked all the time.
Where was the favorite hitchhiking location?
near the campus in order to go to Austin?

Right over there, well, Highway 6 if you're going to Houston, obviously, but if you weren't, right over where the Doodyville Ag Building is, right over that railroad hump, you'd hitchhike on that, but you'd get back over to, gosh, I forgot the highway number that went to Bastrop.
Was there a protocol for Aggie hitchhiking?
Not particularly.
But if you're already there and I come up
Can I go out in front of you?
No, you stand in line.
But there normally weren't more than, I don't recall more than three or four Aggies.
Normally you picked up with one car.
Did rank matter?
Class?
Not that I recall.
I understand that it... No, I never heard of that.
Did you ever hear of anybody having any problems hitchhiking?
Not one time.
And today we'd be horrified.
You know, it's funny...
Normally the hitchhikers are more at risk than the one driving the car because I've hitchhiked with a couple of grumps a few times and I was always kind of nervous.
But today the driver of the car probably is more at risk than the hitchhiker, but in those days the hitchhiker was the one at risk.
All right, now this was an all-male campus in those days.
Where did an Aggie get a date?
Well, various places.
The myth is that Texas Women's University or TSCW at that time, I knew very few Aggies who dated Galsmer.
Most of us.
I made migrations down here at the University of Texas.
My mother had gone here, had strong ties with UT, to today.
I just loved the place, and they had the best looking women, I thought.
Were Aggie, was it okay for a UT female to date an Aggie?
Not, you know, I tell you, it was a little bit of a stigma.
They caught a lot of flack.

the girls did the girls the UT girls they used to call it a flag but by and large not too much the male students at UT really looked down upon us big time as being the country cousins which is not just true in Texas it's true in almost any land grant school I hear the same stories when I talk with people from Auburn for example or other land grant schools as compared to the main university Iowa State Kansas State it was mostly now when you came over to Austin what did you wear
Oh, I'd always be in civilian clothes.
In other words, the rules were as a freshman, you'd have to be 20 miles off campus before you'd get out of your uniform.
I think as a sophomore on, you could hitch out in on red, but you'd put a uniform on because it's easier to get a ride.
But as soon as we got off campus, I might come in my uniform all the way to my grandparents' house here in Austin, but as soon as I got there, I changed.
When a young lady came to College Station for a date, where did she stay?
Well, there were hotels around.
and a lot of private families, private homes or places, but mostly we'd keep them in hotels.
There weren't too many around, but there were a lot of motels.
What were the special events for which you would want to have a date?
Well, they had the junior ball, the sophomore ball, the military ball, and the rain dance.
Those were the big three.
Where were those held?
Describe them.
Mostly Spesa, Spesa Hall.
They were just like they were back in the 20s, 30s.
I think Spesa Hall had been probably the site of more...
dances and parties at A&M than any other building in history or past, present, or future at A&M.
But those were the three that were the big occasions.
How did you Aggies behave at one of those dances?
Oh, like gentlemen.
Did young ladies enjoy coming to?
Oh, blew their mind.
Absolutely blew their mind.
Just today.
And what did they wear?
Well, when you look at those formals, you know, which are about 10 feet wide at the bottom and
Two feet wide at the top, there's just a lot of fluff and colors and all sorts of things.
Typical 50s deal.
50s was my favorite decade of my lifetime.
Let's see.
Describe the community of College Station around the campus.
Describe what was at Northgate and Southgate and Eastgate.
Actually, I'm pretty well qualified to do that.
I married a Bryan girl.
I call it the Bryan girl, whose father was a contractor who built a lot of the buildings in and around the campus at College Station.
So after I got married, which was one year out of A&M, I really kind of learned just a lot from him, a lot of the community life in both College Station and Bryan.
College Station was strictly a college town.
I imagine that 80 or a very high percentage of the people who lived there were associated in one way or the other with the college.
Bryan was a little bit different.
Bryan was an old East Texas town.
It didn't have quite as strong ties to A&M as College Station did.
But even then, it was really basically one metropolitan area.
Brown was about 20,000, 30,000, and College Station was probably 6,000 or 7,000.
But you could hardly tell the difference between the two communities.
But what was there, if you wanted to walk off campus, what was there to eat or entertain?
It was bad.
It was grim.
I only remember two eating places that you'd ever want to eat at off campus.
A place called Zaropi's, which was a Mexican food place.
Where was that?
It was close to the campus.
I don't remember exactly where it was.
Probably a little bit, as I recall, it was east of Highway 6.
And on big occasions, we'd go to Zaropi's or Werman's, W-H-R-M-A-N, Werman's, which is a chicken fried steak place.
And you'd get a chicken fried steak that'd cover a whole plate for a buck.
So those were the two places, the only two places I had any recollection of eating off campus.
Was Lupo yet in business?
Oh, sure.
Where was he at?
Well, Lupo had the same place over there in...
Northgate.
Northgate.

In fact, it's kind of funny, when I was a senior in high school and had been accepted at A&M, and I used accepted kind of loosely because it didn't take too much to be accepted, but I started getting all this mail from vendors around campus, and Lupo was the only one whose advertisement said he would take 50% off on books, and all of them said 40%, so I went to Lupo's.
And the first thing I did when I got on campus was to buy all my engineering books at Lupo's.
That was a 55.
Did you ever meet him?
Oh, sure.
Describe him.
Oh, gosh.
Personality.
Oh, he was a back slapper.
He had friends in high places.
He was kind of funny.
I don't think he ever achieved economic greatness or intellectual greatness, but everybody liked him.
He was just the main figure on the campus, kind of like Pinky Downs was before I got there.
